One patient needed a reintervention. This was a 17-year-old patient with a grade III BTAIs following a high-speed motor vehicle accident (Figure 1
). Associated injuries included a closed head injury, multiple rib fractures with left pulmonary contusion, left kidney and splenic lacerations, and a pelvic fracture. On preintervention CTA measurements, the diameter of the proximal aortic neck was 22 mm, the diameter of the distal neck was 18 mm, and the distance from the LSA was 6 mm. The patient had early endovascular repair of his BTAIs during the first 24 hours. A 24 × 112mm Valiant endograft (Medtronic) was implanted that covered the origin of the LSA (Figure 1). Follow-up CTA at 1 and 6 months showed successful exclusion of the pseudoaneurysm with no endoleaks. Approximately 1 year later, the patient developed significant hypertension and started complaining about symptoms of intermittent claudication. The Doppler ultrasound examination revealed 60 mm Hg pressure gradient between the right arm and the ankle level. A repeat CTA showed a diaphragm at the distal part of the stent graft that was the cause of the pseudocoarctation syndrome (Figure 2
). The patient had already been started on 3 antihypertensives by the referring physician to control hypertension, and he was also placed on clopidogrel. Laboratory test results for congenital or acquired thrombophilia were negative. A second endovascular procedure was planned and a custom-made stent graft 24 × 60mm (Cook Medical) was inserted and deployed via the left femoral artery to cover the flap (Figure 2). Placement of the endograft was uneventful, the lumen expanded easily and postdeployment balloon dilatation was performed with a Coda balloon (Cook Medical). Immediate postoperative improvement of patient’s hypertension and symptoms was noticed and the patient remains clinically well 6 months later. He is currently on no medication apart from aspirin 80 mg OD.

Two late deaths have been reported during the follow-up period; both deaths were not related to the aortic stent graft. Actuarial survival estimates and freedom from reintervention at 5 years were 88.7% and 95.8%, respectively (Figures 3 and 4

). All patients had had predischarge CTA but 4 of them refused to have any further radiological follow-up. The morphometric analysis of stent grafts in the 20 patients with postdischarge follow-up showed no late endoleaks, migration, and stent fractures of collapse. A degree of “bird beak” configuration was noticed—defined as a wedge-shaped gap between the undersurface of the stent graft and the inner curvature of the aortic arch—but this was limited even in patients with highly angulated arches (Figure 5
). The proximal bare metal spring facilitated good apposition of the proximal edge of the fabric with the arterial wall, but it was protruding itself into the aortic arch, crossing the ostia of the LSA, and/or left common carotid artery (Figure 5). In 3 cases, we noticed short dissection-like flaps, linear, or circumferential thrombus at the distal part of the stent graft (Figure 6
). These lesions had no clinical sequelae.
